Notes on KIPP College Match Algorithm¶

Version: 2
Updated: 8/8/19

Reverse-Engineering¶

Purpose¶

  • Categorizes Colleges by Odds of Admission based upon a students GPA and Test Scores.
  • The system also considers geographic location, the colleges graduation rate, the students financial means, and which colleges the student is interested in.

System Inputs¶

  • Unweighted GPA: Float value between 1.50 and 4.30.
  • ACT: Integer value between 11 and 36.
  • SAT (EBRW + M)*: Integer value between 590 and 1600. Mapped to an ACT score via a lookup table.

Following are not used for core functionality but just enable filtering of the result set:

  • Annual Family Income
    • 0 - \$30K
    • \$30K - \$48K
    • \$48K - \$75K
  • City: A list of cities is available on the Lat and Long sheet

System Outputs¶

  • A list of colleges categorized into Likely+, Likely, Target, and Reach.
    • Likely+: 80% to 100% odds of admission + High Grad Rate
    • Likely: 80% to 100% odds of admission
    • Target: 50% to 79% odds of admission
    • Reach: 15% to 49% odds of admission

  • The Unlikely designation is not included in the KIPP system, but is added for schools with less than 15% odds of admission.
    • Unlikely: <14% odds of admission

The Algorithm¶

Consider example of a Harvard applicant with a 4.25 GPA and a 29 ACT.

$$Logit_{Harvard}=GPA_{coef}*GPA + ACT_{coef}*(ACT-ACT_{adj})+intercept$$
$$Logit_{Harvard}=(4.2009)(4.25)+(0.2751)(29-32)-17.92$$
$$Logit_{Harvard}=-0.891475$$

The "Odds" of admission is calculated from this "Logit" term.

$$Odds_{Harvard}=\frac{e^{logit}}{1+e^{logit}}$$
$$Odds_{Harvard}=\frac{e^{?0.891475}}{1+e^{?0.891475}}$$
$$Odds_{Harvard}=29.08\%$$

In this example, the 29.08% "Odds" given to this Harvard applicant would place him in the Reach category for Harvard.

Other examples in the table printed below.

Note: The $GPA_{coef}$, $ACT_{coef}$, $Intercept$, and $ACT_{adj}$ appear to be KIPP property or derived from some other document. Where these values come from is unclear based on the Excel file we have. The data is simply in the file as raw data, like a copy-paste with values only.

It is also unclear how our data could be used to update these values. Based upon the way these parameters are labeled, they appear to be terms taken from a linear regression based on applications data that KIPP or some other organization have.

Coefficients, Intercepts and Concepts¶

This section breaks down the distribution of the coefficients, intercepts, and ACT adjustments just discussed.

The two coefficients and the intercept appear to group with one another. ACT_adj does not group with the rest of them.

All other parameters in the tool appear to be used to filter the various colleges based on items like

  • 6-year African-American/Hispanic Grad rate,
  • number of undergrads,
  • cost to attend,
  • distance from current location, etc.

The data that back up the tool appears fairly robust, but clearly broken for some schools.

Create Graphs¶

Solve for Values of Logit and for the crucial Odds Thresholds

$$\frac{e^{logit}}{1+e^{logit}}=Odds$$
In [6]:
import sympy as sy
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
In [7]:
def f(x):
    return np.exp(x)/(1+np.exp(x))*100

x = np.arange(-5,5,0.05)
plt.figure(figsize=(4,3))
plt.xlabel('Logit')
plt.ylabel('Odds (%)')
plt.plot(x, f(x), 'r-')
plt.show()
for n in range(-5, 6, 1):
    print('When Logit =  {}, Odds = '.format(n) + str(int(round(f(n)))) + " %")

When Logit =  -5, Odds = 1 %
When Logit =  -4, Odds = 2 %
When Logit =  -3, Odds = 5 %
When Logit =  -2, Odds = 12 %
When Logit =  -1, Odds = 27 %
When Logit =  0, Odds = 50 %
When Logit =  1, Odds = 73 %
When Logit =  2, Odds = 88 %
When Logit =  3, Odds = 95 %
When Logit =  4, Odds = 98 %
When Logit =  5, Odds = 99 %
In [8]:
x = sy.Symbol('x')
In [9]:
logit_likely = float(sy.solve((sy.exp(x)/(1+sy.exp(x)))-.8,x)[0])
logit_target = float(sy.solve((sy.exp(x)/(1+sy.exp(x)))-.5,x)[0])
logit_reach = float(sy.solve((sy.exp(x)/(1+sy.exp(x)))-.15,x)[0])
In [10]:
print('Likely Odds: 80%, logit = ' + str(logit_likely))
print('Target Odds: 50%, logit = ' + str(logit_target))
print('Reach Odds:  15%, logit = ' + str(logit_reach))

Likely Odds: 80%, logit = 1.3862943611198906
Target Odds: 50%, logit = 0.0
Reach Odds:  15%, logit = -1.7346010553881064

Plot the curves for these various values of Logit¶

Independent Variable: GPA, because it is difficult to dramatically impact at time of college applications.
Dependent Variable: ACT, because it can be improved.

$$(GPA_{coef})(GPA) + (ACT_{coef})(ACT-ACT_{adj})+intercept-logit = 0$$


$$ACT = ACT_{adj} + \frac{logit - intercept - (GPA_{coef})(GPA)}{ACT_{coef}}$$

In [12]:
gpa_range = np.arange(1.5, 4.4, .1)
In [13]:
# Solves for ACT required for GPA values
def constant_ei(gpa, ei):
    return (ei - 200.*gpa)/10.
In [14]:
# Solves for ACT required for GPA values
def act_for_gpa(gpa, gpa_coef, act_coef, act_adj, inter, logit):
    return act_adj + (logit - inter - gpa_coef*gpa)/act_coef
In [15]:
def draw_lines(ax, gpa, gpa_coef, act_coef, act_adj, inter):
    lines = []
    for logit in [logit_likely, 
                  logit_target, 
                  logit_reach]:
        lines.append(act_for_gpa(gpa_range,
                                 gpa_coef,
                                 act_coef,
                                 act_adj,
                                 inter,
                                 logit))
    for color, line, label in [('b-',lines[0],'Safety (80+% odds)'),
                               ('g-',lines[1],'Target (50+% odds)'),
                               ('y-',lines[2],'Reach (15+% odds)')]:
        ax.plot(gpa_range, 
                line, 
                color,
                linewidth=0.5,
                label=label)
    ax.fill_between(gpa_range, 36, lines[0],
                    facecolor='lightblue')
    ax.fill_between(gpa_range, lines[0], lines[1],
                    facecolor='lightgreen')
    ax.fill_between(gpa_range, lines[1], lines[2],
                    facecolor='lightyellow')
    
    for ei, xy, label in [(500.,(1.5,20.),None),
                          (600.,(1.5,30.),None),
                          (700.,(1.7,36.),None),
                          (800.,(2.2,36.),None),
                          (900.,(2.7,36.),None),
                          (1000.,(3.2,36.),None),
                          (1100.,(3.7,36.),None),
                          (1200.,(4.2,36.),'Constant EI')]:
        ax.plot(gpa_range,
                constant_ei(gpa_range, ei),
                linewidth=0.25,
                color='0.5',
                label=label)
        ax.annotate(str(int(ei)),
                    xy,
                    textcoords="offset points",
                    xytext=(14,-14.),
                    ha='center',
                    va='center',
                    color='0.65',
                    rotation=-59.51)
        
    ax.legend(loc='lower right',
          framealpha=1.0,
          edgecolor='w')

def save_figure(university):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,7.5))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(1,1,1)
    draw_lines(ax       = ax,
               gpa      = gpa_range,
               gpa_coef = float(c.loc[university]['GPA_coef']),
               act_coef = float(c.loc[university]['ACT_coef']),
               act_adj  = float(c.loc[university]['ACT_adj']),
               inter    = float(c.loc[university]['Intercept']))
    ax.set_ylabel('ACT')
    ax.set_xlabel('GPA')
    ax.set_ylim(11,36)
    ax.set_xlim(1.5,4.3)
    ax.set_xticks(np.arange(1.5,4.4,0.1))
    for label in ax.xaxis.get_ticklabels()[::2]:
        label.set_visible(False)
    ax.tick_params(axis='x')#,
                #   labelrotation=90.0)
    ax.set_yticks(np.arange(11,37,1))
    for label in ax.yaxis.get_ticklabels()[::2]:
        label.set_visible(False)

    left_title =\
    'Tier ' + str(c.loc[university]['Tier'].astype(int)) + ' '\
    + c.loc[university]['Category'] + '\n'\
    + 'Barrons: ' + c.loc[university]['Barrons'] + '\n'\
    + c.loc[university]['City'] + ', ' + c.loc[university]['State']
    right_title =\
    'Net Cost: $' + str(int(round(c.loc[university]['NetPriceAverage Income']/1000))) + 'K\n'\
    + '6-Year Minority Retention: ' + str(int(round(c.loc[university]['Adj_6yr_AAH']))) +'%\n'\
    + 'Overall Retention: ' + str(int(round(c.loc[university]['Retention']))) +'%'

    plt.title(left_title, loc='left')
    plt.title(university + '\n\n\n',fontweight="bold")
    plt.title(right_title, loc='right')
    ax.grid(True,
            linewidth=0.25,
            color='0.5')
    ax.tick_params(axis='both',
                   width=0.25,
                   color='0.5')
    ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines['bottom'].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines['left'].set_visible(False)
    
    plt.annotate('Updated: 8/12/19',
                 (0,0), (0, -20), xycoords='axes fraction', 
                 textcoords='offset points', va='top')
    
    fig.savefig('outputs/'+str(c.loc[university]['Tier'].astype(int)) + ' '\
                + c.loc[university]['Category'] + ' '\
                + university + '.pdf',
                bbox_inches='tight',
                pad_inches=0.5);

$$ACT = ACT_{adj} + \frac{logit - intercept - (GPA_{coef})(GPA)}{ACT_{coef}}$$
